README.md
# clap
A zero-dependency, single-header library for parsing command line arguments in C.

## Features
- Zero dependencies
- Single header file
- Supports short (`-a`) and long (`--arg`) options
- Supports positional arguments
- Supports subcommands
- Supports required and optional arguments
- Supports default values
- Supports help text
- Supports multiple arguments (e.g. `-a 1 -a 2`)
- Supports argument aliases
- Supports custom type parsers
- Supports usage strings

## Usage

```c
#define CLAP_IMPL
#include "clap.h"

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    clap_parser parser;
    clap_parser_init(&parser, argc, argv, (clap_option){0});

    // Define your command line interface
    clap_arg args[] = {
        {
            .names = {"help", "h"},
            .description = "Display this help message",
            .is_flag = true,
            .aliases = {"?"} // alias for help
        },
        {
            .names = {"verbose", "v"},
            .description = "Enable verbose output",
            .is_flag = true
        },
        {
            .names = {"output", "o"},
            .description = "Output file",
            .takes_values = true,
            .required = true
        },
        {
            .names = {"count", "c"},
            .description = "Count",
            .takes_values = true,
            .value = "1"
        }
    };

    // Parse the arguments
    clap_parse(&parser, args, sizeof(args)/sizeof(args[0]));

    // Check if help was requested
    if (clap_contains(&parser, "help") || clap_contains(&parser, "?")) {
        clap_help(&parser, args, sizeof(args)/sizeof(args[0]));
        return 0;
    }

    // Get values
    const char *output = clap_get(&parser, "output");
    const char *count = clap_get(&parser, "count");
    int verbose = clap_contains(&parser, "verbose");

    // Use the values
    printf("Output: %s\n", output);
    printf("Count: %s\n", count);
    printf("Verbose: %s\n", verbose ? "true" : "false");

    clap_free(&parser);

    return 0;
}
```

## Building

clap is a single header library. To use it, simply include the header file and define `CLAP_IMPL` in one source file.

```bash
gcc -o myprogram main.c
```

## API

### Types

```c
typedef struct {
    const char *name;
    const char *value;
    int count;
    const char **values;
} clap_arg_value;

typedef struct {
    const char *name;
    const char *value;
    int count;
    const char **values;
} clap_arg_value;

typedef enum {
    CLAP_NONE = 0,
    CLAP_REQUIRED = 1 << 0,
    CLAP_FLAG = 1 << 1,
    CLAP_POSITIONAL = 1 << 2,
    CLAP_MULTIPLE = 1 << 3,
    CLAP_HIDDEN = 1 << 4,
} clap_option;

typedef struct clap_arg {
    const char **names;
    const char *description;
    const char *value;
    clap_option flags;
    clap_option aliases[8];
    clap_parser_func parser;
    void *data;
} clap_arg;
```

### Functions

```c
// Initialize the parser
void clap_parser_init(clap_parser *parser, int argc, char **argv, clap_option options);

// Parse command line arguments
void clap_parse(clap_parser *parser, clap_arg *args, int arg_count);

// Check if an argument was provided
int clap_contains(clap_parser *parser, const char *name);

// Get the value of an argument
const char *clap_get(clap_parser *parser, const char *name);

// Get all values of an argument (for multiple arguments)
